Dr. Zhu’s group improved the surface quality of Sn–Pb mixed perovskites by adding phenethylammonium iodide (PEAI) and GASCN together [44]. The reaction between the two additives formed a quasi-2D structure of PEA2GAPb2I7. The surface morphology was noticeably enhanced owing to the quasi-2D structure of the 3D perovskite, and the under-coordinated B-site defects (Sn2+ and Pb2+) were passivated. In Fig. 7b, the surface recombination velocity and bulk recombination lifetime were calculated through TRPL measurements by thickness, based on Eq. (1) [58]:11τTRPL=1τb+2Sd\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{1}{{\tau }_{\mathrm{TRPL}}}=\frac{1}{{\tau }_{\mathrm{b}}}+\frac{2S}{d}$$\end{document}where τTRPL is the measured TRPL lifetime, τb is the bulk recombination lifetime, S is the surface recombination velocity, and d is the film thickness. The S calculated by the equation was very low at 1.4 cm s−1, and the bulk recombination lifetime was 9.2 μs. A low value of S corresponds to a lifetime of 30 μs for surface recombination velocity, meaning that very minimal recombination occurs on the surface.
